🔐 TRUST BOUNDARIES
Trust Boundary 1: Internet → API
Threat: user manipulation
Trust Boundary 2: Producer → Event Bus
Threat: forged events
Trust Boundary 3: Event Bus → Consumers
Threat: replay, tampering, poisoning
Trust Boundary 4: Consumer → Internal DB
Threat: duplicate processing, logic abuse

1️⃣ Event Signing — Why & How
Threat
If event bus allows publishing from multiple services, attacker who compromises one service could:
	• Publish fake PaymentApproved
	• Publish fake RefundCompleted
Consumers may trust event blindly.
Async systems assume:
	“If it’s on the bus, it’s legitimate.”
That assumption is dangerous.

Secure Flow With Signing

Payment Service:
    event_payload = {...}
    signature = HMAC(event_payload, private_key)
    publish(event_payload + signature)
Consumer:

verify_signature(event_payload, signature, producer_public_key)
if invalid → reject
Why signing?
Because the event bus itself does not guarantee integrity.
It guarantees delivery, not authenticity.
Why not rely only on network isolation?
Because:
	• Internal compromise happens.
	• Lateral movement is real.
	• Zero Trust assumes breach.
Memory anchor:
	Event bus guarantees transport.
	Signing guarantees authenticity.

2️⃣ Replay Protection — Why It Matters
Async systems are vulnerable to replay.
Attacker captures valid event:

PaymentApproved: $10,000
Replays it 50 times.
Without replay protection:
Ledger updates 50 times.

Secure Flow With Replay Protection
Producer adds:
	• event_id (UUID)
	• timestamp
	• nonce
Consumer maintains:
	• Processed event_id store (cache/DB)
Flow:

if event_id already processed:
    discard
else:
    process and store event_id
Why not just rely on Kafka offset?
Because:
	• Consumer restarts.
	• Multiple consumer groups.
	• Attacker might inject same event with new offset.
Replay protection is logical-layer defense.
Memory anchor:
	Delivery systems prevent loss.
	They do not prevent replay abuse.

3️⃣ Idempotency — Why It Is Different From Replay Protection
Replay protection checks:
“Have I seen this exact event before?”
Idempotency ensures:
“If I process it twice, the result is still correct.”
Example:
Instead of:

balance = balance - amount
Use:

if transaction_id not processed:
    deduct and mark processed
Or use:

update ledger where transaction_id = X
Idempotency protects against:
	• Consumer crash
	• Network retry
	• Duplicate publish
Replay protection blocks malicious replay.
Idempotency protects against accidental duplication.
Both are required.
Memory anchor:
	Replay protection blocks malicious duplicates.
	Idempotency neutralizes accidental duplicates.

4️⃣ Poison Message Handling
Poison message = event that always fails processing.
Example:
Malformed payload.
Schema mismatch.
Business logic error.
If consumer keeps retrying:
	• CPU exhaustion
	• Infinite retry loop
	• Pipeline blockage
Secure design:

if message fails N times:
    move to Dead Letter Queue
Why not retry forever?
Because async systems can self-DoS via bad messages.

5️⃣ Dead-Letter Queue (DLQ)
DLQ is an isolated topic/queue.
Flow:

Main Topic → Consumer → Failure threshold → DLQ
Security purpose:
	• Isolate problematic events.
	• Prevent system stall.
	• Allow forensic analysis.
Threat if absent:
One malicious event blocks entire pipeline.
Memory anchor:
	DLQ prevents single-event denial of service.

6️⃣ Consumer Isolation
Modern mistake:
Multiple services consume from same topic with broad privileges.
Risk:
If one consumer compromised:
	• It can produce events.
	• It may read sensitive events.
	• It may inject forged ones.
Secure design:
	• Separate IAM roles per consumer.
	• Topic-level access control.
	• Network segmentation.
	• Separate consumer groups.
ASCII concept:

Fraud Service IAM → read payments topic only
Ledger Service IAM → read payments topic only
No cross-publish rights
Why?
Because event bus is lateral movement highway.
Memory anchor:
	Async systems amplify compromise blast radius.
Isolation reduces blast radius.

