🧠 Why Modern Systems Are Async-First (And Why Security Is Harder)
Async gives:
	• Scalability
	• Fault tolerance
	• Decoupling
But removes:
	• Immediate transaction visibility
	• Simple request-response validation
	• Centralized control
Security must move from:
Request-time validation → Event lifecycle validation.

If asked:
“How do you secure an event-driven architecture?”
You answer:
“In async systems, we must secure authenticity, integrity, and processing semantics. Producers sign events to ensure authenticity across trust boundaries. Consumers verify signatures before processing. 
Replay protection is implemented using unique event IDs and nonce tracking. Idempotency ensures duplicate processing does not corrupt state. 
Poison messages are isolated using retry thresholds and dead-letter queues to prevent denial-of-service. Finally, strict IAM isolation and topic-level access control reduce lateral movement risk. 
Since modern architectures are async-first, event security must enforce Zero Trust principles across the entire event lifecycle.”
